PAUL, of course it is a soul deep decision from personal conscsiencious (sp?). Vets are vets, and choose, or were drafted into the jungle. I, and many like me, choose to stand up to our government gone wrong, and risk imprisonment or worse.  Now 30 years later, we try and sort out the deck. It is hard, brother, very hard.  Many protestors went off the deep end, bombing edison towers in some misguided mission, or drafte induction centers, other fled to Canada, (and I do not consider them), while others stood up to the FBI when it came a callin' at the front door, and told it to go to hell.  My father actually hosed them off with a hose.<br>
So there is no one answer, all I know is what is in my heart, and that was the war was wrong, and I wanted to keep as many of my brother generation members, even though they were refusing to think, from going. Did you ever lay down on the tracks of a train?  Feel the rumbling coming through the iron rails, knowing the conductor or engineer would love to slap the throttle foward and cut our heads off, americans killing americans, is as close as I came to death in the jungle.  But death, unnatural death, isn't it all the same, whether or not it is a AK-47 or an M-16 that shoots you?<br><br>
